%S A265495 1,2,7,6,14,29
%N A265495 a(n) is the smallest k > 0 for which there exists a root quad (-k,x,y,z) such that some bend is first repeated in the n-th generation of descendants (by Descartes reflection).
%C A265495 Perhaps a(0) should be 0, for the quad (0,0,1,1).
%C A265495 Functions were written in the statistical language R to generate root quads and to generate successive generations of descendants. The n-th generation (n >= 1) contains 4*3^(n-1) quads.
%H A265495 R. L. Graham, J. C. Lagarias, C. L. Mallows, Allan Wilks and C. H. Yan, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0009113">Apollonian Circle Packings: Number Theory</a>, arXiv:math/0009113 [math.NT], 2000-2003.
%H A265495 R. L. Graham, J. C. Lagarias, C. L. Mallows, Allan Wilks and C. H. Yan, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0022-314X(03)00015-5">Apollonian Circle Packings: Number Theory</a>, J. Number Theory, 100 (2003), 1-45.
%e A265495 For n = 0,1,2,3,4,5, qualifying root quads are (-1,2,2,3), (-2,3,6,7), (-7,12,17,20), (-6,11,14,15), (-14,19,54,55), (-29,55,60,70). E.g., for n=3, the bend 71 appears in both the second and third generations, in the quads (-6,14,35,71) and (-6,11,42,71).
